<subSubSection id="09F9B335A9BB56C2FE1D708AF2C7EE94" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="4EFD06E299CFB141984757CC9E270CCA" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9239B011E8AF4388AB8720508453DBD4" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
This species varies remarkably in size, from 12-21 mm in total length, to 3-5 mm in maximum width. In Macau, adults are active throughout the warmer parts of the year, from April till November. Larvae are reported to develop in pine trees, 
<taxonomicName id="0B34C425A0CB3AFDB78B72E64DBD616C" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FAC910D40037F8AB3056326B1938825F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Pinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<bibRefCitation id="FF65CF79F02309CD89D9C6F0EA43CE87" author="Yiu, V" journalOrPublisher="Hong Kong Entomological Society, Hong Kong" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B161" refString="Yiu, V, 2009. Longhorn Beetles of Hong Kong. Insect Fauna of Hong Kong, Fascicle 1. Hong Kong Entomological Society, Hong Kong" title="Longhorn Beetles of Hong Kong. Insect Fauna of Hong Kong, Fascicle 1." year="2009">Yiu 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="226DD90FEA85672474BB6385C7E1F6E0" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5656/KSAE.2013.11.1.061" author="Lim, J" journalOrPublisher="Korean Journal of Applied Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="111 - 133" refId="B87" refString="Lim, J, Jung, S-Y, Lim, J-S, Jang, J, Kim, K-M, Lee, Y-M, Lee, B-W, 2014. A Review of Host Plants of Cerambycidae (Coleoptera: Chrysomeloidea) with new Host Records for Fourteen Cerambycids, Including the Asian Longhorn Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis Motschulsky), in Korea. Korean Journal of Applied Entomology 53 (2): 111 - 133, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5656/KSAE.2013.11.1.061" title="A Review of Host Plants of Cerambycidae (Coleoptera: Chrysomeloidea) with new Host Records for Fourteen Cerambycids, Including the Asian Longhorn Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis Motschulsky), in Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.5656/KSAE.2013.11.1.061" volume="53" year="2014">Lim et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) but have not been reported as causing damage to plantations or becoming invasive.
</paragraph>
